The gotchas: user I-Ds, and the Mac and Windows sync caveat.

Two problems bite almost everyone who uses bind mounts, and both come from the boundary between the container and the host.

The first is user-I-D and group-I-D ownership. A container's process runs as some numeric user I-D, whatever the image's user setting says, often zero, which is root, or a fixed I-D like nine ninety-nine. When that process writes to a bind-mounted host path, the host records the write as that same numeric user I-D, because, by default, Docker does not remap user I-Ds. User-namespace remapping is opt-in, and that's module eight. So a container running as root that writes a file leaves it owned by root on your host. One running as nine ninety-nine leaves it owned by nine ninety-nine, which is some random local user, or nobody. The standard fixes are: match user I-Ds, by running with dash u and your own host user and group, so files come out owned by you; or pre-create the host directory with permissive ownership for dev, which is fine for dev, but not for production.

The second is the Mac and Windows sync caveat. On Linux, the container and host share the kernel, so a bind mount is essentially free; the container sees the host inode directly. But on macOS and Windows, Docker runs a hidden Linux virtual machine, and it has to bridge the host filesystem into it. That bridge is slow. An n-p-m install over a bind-mounted node-modules can be five to ten times slower than on native Linux. The mitigations, in order: first, put hot directories, like node-modules or a build target, into named volumes, and bind-mount only the source you actually edit; that's the common production-quality pattern. Second, use the cached or delegated consistency options on your binds, for a speed win where strict ordering between host and container doesn't matter.

And that's the through-line of the whole module: volumes for data you keep, bind mounts for code you edit. And when a bind mount misbehaves, it's almost always user I-Ds, or the virtual-machine bridge.
